post_text:
Bryan vs. TCC
Final score: Bryan 2-3 TCC

Today was a tale of two halves. The girls started strong, dominated possession and controlled the game for the first 40 minutes of play. They continued to apply pressure and push forward creating multiple opportunities. #6 Delilah Taylor put us in the lead after beating a few defenders outside the box and finding the far corner. A few minutes later, #19 Ella Voigt fired a long ball into the box that #12 Allie Zimmerman chased down and poked past the keeper to make it 2-0 at halftime. Unfortunately, we let off the gas at the start of the second half and when they scored their first from a free kick 30 yards out, our heads sank, and we couldn’t recover. A couple defensive mistakes allowed their second goal to be scored off another free kick that ended with a loose ball in the box that TCC cleaned up with a goal. And their 3rd goal was a shot outside the box.
Tough game where we played well in the first half but couldn’t stay consistent through the second.

JH Cross Country
Both boys and girls cross-country teams were victorious over Archbold at a two-way meet at the Archbold reservoir.

In the girls' race, Bryan won with a score of 16 to 45. Kate Thormeier led the way with a first place finish in 14:51. Other finishers were Ava Zimmerman in 2nd, Ava Lambert in 3rd, Caitlyn DeWitt in 4th, Josey Arnold in 6th, Kelby Knight in 7th, Casey Xie in 10th, and Drew Smith in 12th.

In the boys' race, Bryan won with a score of 24 to 33. Gunner Davis paced the team with a 2nd place finish in 14:15. Other finishers were Nye Bradbee in 3rd, Corey Minck in 4th, Collin Rachel in 7th, Dominic Young in 8th, Jack Kennedy in 9th, Will Roberts in 15th, and John Dalrymple in 18th.

The team will be back in action on Tuesday afternoon at the Golden Bear Invitational.

post_text:
Final score: Bryan 5-2 Delta

Girls Soccer
A solid performance from the girls tonight and a much needed win to boost our confidence for the remainder of the season. We controlled possession throughout the game and were able to create numerous chances on the attack. The deadlock was broken by #6 Delilah Taylor in the 25th minute. Shortly thereafter she found the net again to make it 2-0 going into half. #0 Bre Long had one save in the first half and recorded her first clean sheet of the season. The girls continued to apply pressure and control the game during the second half and made it 3-0 after #2 Ella Miller dropped it back to #20 Kailee Thiel who chipped it over the keeper’s head. #2 Ella Miller found the net for herself soon after to put us up 4-0.
Delta was able to claw a couple goals back in the 60th and 64th minutes of the game making it 4-2. However, the game was put to bed when #12 Allie Zimmerman headed a loose ball home in the 73rd minute of play.
Overall great performance and a step in the direction for the girls.

post_text:
Girls Soccer
Final score: Shawnee 5-0 Bryan

Tonight’s game was certainly one to learn from. The girls started slow and were not able to recover. Shawnee played a good game and outworked us to the ball all around the field. The girls continued to fight through the end of the game but we couldn’t quite find the extra gear we needed to maintain possession and move the ball up the field. Although the scoreline may not reflect well on the team, the game provided us with area’s to improve upon moving forward. I am confident we can bounce back from our first loss of the season. Despite our struggles tonight, #0 Bre Long recorded four saves and #1 Calysta Wasson had one.

On Thursday, August 27, at 6 pm, Bryan City Schools will host a virtual meeting welcoming Patrick King and Phil Trueblood from Stifel, Nicolaus & Co, Incorporated, the underwriter on the District’s upcoming bond issue, to speak.
Patrick King and Phil Trueblood will present information to interested community members on the upcoming school bond sale and provide information to interested community members as to how they can purchase the District’s upcoming refinancing bonds. The District provided a similar opportunity to community members ahead of the 2014 bond sale and the interest from local investors at that time warranted revisiting the initiative for this refinancing.

post_text: The Bryan Golfers competed in the Paulding Invitational at Auglaize. The Bears shot 331 and finished in 3rd place behind Wauseon 328, and Kalida 326. Nolan Kidston was low man with 78, Nathan Hess and Drew Dauber both carded 83, Noah Huard shot 87, Carter Brown shot 90.

post_text: The Bryan Golfers won the Patrick Henry Invite today with a team score of 317. Liberty Benton finished second with 321. Nolan Kidston led the way with a 75 (2nd overall) followed by Clayton Rupp 78, Drew Dauber 80, Noah Huard 84 and Nate Hess 87. Congrats Bears!!

post_text:
High School Golf tryouts will be the following dates and times. You will need to have a physical on file with Mrs. Kuszmaul and the athletic office in order to try out. Physical Forms may be picked up at the Event Entrance. Your parents must have done the on-line registration including the athletic part before you can tryout on August 3rd. Make sure these are done before tryouts. Please dress appropriately in golfing attire (Shorts, collared shirt). Bring a water bottle or sports drink. Pull carts are permitted.

Tryouts will be held at Riverside Greens in Stryker.

Monday August 3rd 7:00am 18 holes

Tuesday August 4th 1pm 18 holes

Weds. August 5th 7:00am 18 holes

Thursday August 6th First Match @ Stryker 4:00pm

If you have questions email Coach Grosjean.

Know! To Talk About George Floyd and Racism with Youth

Prevention Action Alliance
June 9 at 8:30 PM ·

George Floyd's death affects us all, including our kids. Talking to our kids about racism can be difficult and uncomfortable, but it's vitally important that we do it. These expert recommendations will help you have this talk with your kids. https://preventionactionalliance.org/advocate/newsletters/know-to-talk-about-george-floyd-and-racism-with-youth/

If you haven’t already done so, ALL RETURNING BRYAN CITY SCHOOLS STUDENTS need to register in our online registration system to prepare for the 2020-2021 school year. This easy and efficient registration process allows us to gather all necessary information about your student(s) for the upcoming 2020-2021 school year. Online Registration can be accessed by logging into your Powerschool Parent Portal or by clicking on the link below.

Incoming 6th graders are reminded that they will be required to use a school-issued Chromebook as they transition into the 2020-2021 school year at the Middle School.

If you have questions, please contact the Central Registrar at 419-633-6218.

Reminder of the graduate parade after graduation TODAY, SUNDAY, MAY 24. Please come out and cheer on our seniors!

The route is designed to give spectators a safe opportunity to see the graduates and therefore the parade route will go through the City of Bryan Park system and past large areas of green space along Avenue A.

ALL current COVID-19 social distancing requirements must be followed during the parade to ensure the safety of our students, parents, community members, and loved ones. THANK YOU in advance for following these guidelines!

Graduates exit the South Entrance/Exit of the Events Lot
Turn Right onto Fountain Grove Drive
Turn Right onto County Road 13
Turn Right onto Center Street
Turn Left into Recreation Park
Follow the Rec Park Street to Oakwood Drive
Turn Right onto Oakwood Drive
Turn Right onto Avenue A
**Parade ends once participants return back to Center Street

post_text:
Hello Seniors and families!!!

PLEASE WATCH this video that shows the process vehicles will follow when graduates will make their way to the stage to receive their diploma at the graduation ceremony!!

Please note: The direction the graduate walks across the stage is now opposite than on the maps Seniors received. This change will allow traffic to flow appropriately.

Reminders:

1.) Make sure that graduates are not driving the vehicle. The graduate MUST be a passenger in the vehicle.

2.) Make sure your vehicle has plenty of gas, the radiator fluid levels are appropriate, and your vehicle battery is fully charged!! (we learned from other schools who did a similar ceremony that this is very important!!!)

3.) Please keep vehicles turned off as much as possible throughout the ceremony.

4.) We encourage graduate vehicles to be decorated to celebrate the day

7.) GRADUATES BE SURE TO WEAR YOUR CAP AND GOWN

HERE IS THE VIDEO LINK TO WATCH: https://youtu.be/d2AQ42GcHPE

post_text:
Attention INCOMING Bryan Preschool students!!

If your child is 3-5 years old during the school year, he or she is eligible to be screened for preschool.

It's time to complete the online registration so that we are sure to have your contact information for the 2020-21 School year.

Go to Bryan City Schools website and click on Registration > Enrollment Procedures>Preschool Registration or click on the link below. You will find a lot of information on this page to help prepare your child for next year. Please make sure you complete the following info on the Preschool Registration page:

1 - Complete the contact information form.
2 - Complete the Online Registration for 2020-21 school year

More information about screening dates will be released once it becomes available.

If you have questions about registration you may email Hulie Stockman, Central Registrar, jstockman@bryanschools.net

This is for next year's Preschool students. Please share if you know one!

We know there have been a lot of questions and concerns regarding graduation and other end of year events. We want you to know that BCS is currently working with local government authorities to develop plans for graduation, prom, and all other end of school year activities. Our school district will continue to follow any requirements and recommendations from the Ohio Department of Education, the Ohio Department of Health, and the Governor's office. Once plans have been finalized, they will be released to the parents and to the community.

Anyone who would like to see the guidelines published by the ODE are welcome to visit their website at the link below

Zeta Cordia
April 16 at 4:30 PM ·

Many of our Golden Bear traditions are beginning to take on a different form this spring due to our current circumstances. You have an amazing graduating class that deserves a ton of recognition!! Therefore, we want our BCS family to meet the BHS Class of 2020, to celebrate your accomplishments, and to learn about your future plans. To help do this we are creating Senior Spotlights!

Please take a few moments to fill out this form with your information and to upload a formal photograph of yourself. Once the information is shared back with us we will post your Senior Spotlight on our district social media accounts. It is our hopes for the Senior Spotlights to then get viewed and shared by the many people who support you.

Thank you!!

shared_text:
Williams County Board of Developmental Disabilities is at Williams County Board of Developmental Disabilities.
April 12 at 4:17 PM · Montpelier, OH ·

The Harvest Market will be giving away boxes of food on Wednesday, April 15 from 10:00-1:00 at The Enrichment Center. It will be different than usual. Customers must stay in their vehicle at all times. Someone from the Harvest Market or a member of the Ohio National Guard will register you, you will pop your trunk/hatch, a member from the National Guard will place the box in your trunk, they will shut it and you will depart. There will be a one box limit per household. Please make sure you have room in your trunk for the box. You won’t be able to get of your vehicle to rearrange it at The Enrichment Center. The Harvest Market is bringing 100 boxes. The Enrichment Center will be closed to the public. A public restroom will NOT be available to customers.

Attention Parents/Guardians: Student lunches will be available for pick up at Bryan Elementary for any district student that qualifies for free or reduced lunches, starting Wednesday, April 1 from 11:00-1:00pm. More information regarding the lunches will be posted on Monday, March 30.

BCS encourages families who are financially impacted by the COVID closures to complete an application for Free/Reduced meals for your students. This program will carry over to the beginning of the new school year as well.

Forms will be available through pick-up or by mail if you contact one of the phone numbers listed in the email sent out today. If you can print, you may also access the form on our website at the following link: https://www.bryan.k12.oh.us/docs/district/19-20%20fr%20app.pdf?id=5407
